<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1910,2006]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
This poorly studied species is known only from few specimens collected in São Paulo (
<figureCitation box="[1178,1266,1910,1934]" captionStart="FIGURES 82 – 92" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1443,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1421]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,193,1422]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 82 – 92. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. varitibia female 82, 85: 82. Dorsal view; 85. Pronotum. H. sanctaecatharinae sp. n. female 83 – 84, 86 – 88: 83. Dorsal view; 84. Mesonotum and metanotum; 86. Head; 87. Pronotum; 88. Antennal segment III. H. condei female 89 – 92: 89. Dorsal view; 90. Antenna; 91. Mesonotum and metanotum; 92. Abdominal sternites IV – VI setae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280421/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[1234,1266,1910,1934]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="82.0">82</number>
</figureCitation>
). The pronotal sculpture is weak (
<figureCitation box="[365,449,1946,1970]" captionStart="FIGURES 82 – 92" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1443,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1421]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,193,1422]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 82 – 92. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. varitibia female 82, 85: 82. Dorsal view; 85. Pronotum. H. sanctaecatharinae sp. n. female 83 – 84, 86 – 88: 83. Dorsal view; 84. Mesonotum and metanotum; 86. Head; 87. Pronotum; 88. Antennal segment III. H. condei female 89 – 92: 89. Dorsal view; 90. Antenna; 91. Mesonotum and metanotum; 92. Abdominal sternites IV – VI setae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280421/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[419,449,1946,1970]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="85.0">85</number>
</figureCitation>
), and abdominal tergite IX is remarkably longer than X (
<figureCitation box="[1102,1188,1946,1970]" captionStart="FIGURES 82 – 92" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1443,1466]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1421]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,193,1422]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 82 – 92. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. varitibia female 82, 85: 82. Dorsal view; 85. Pronotum. H. sanctaecatharinae sp. n. female 83 – 84, 86 – 88: 83. Dorsal view; 84. Mesonotum and metanotum; 86. Head; 87. Pronotum; 88. Antennal segment III. H. condei female 89 – 92: 89. Dorsal view; 90. Antenna; 91. Mesonotum and metanotum; 92. Abdominal sternites IV – VI setae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280421/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[1156,1188,1946,1970]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="82.0">82</number>
</figureCitation>
). Males are similar to females in coloration and lack pore plates on abdominal sternites.
</paragraph>
